doc.after: Following his appointment to the Chair of Electrical Engineering at Manchester University, Williams recruited his TRE colleague Tom Kilburn on secondment. By the autumn of 1947 the pair had increased the storage capacity of the Williams tube from one bit to 2,048, arranged in a 64 by 32-bit array,[20] and demonstrated that it was able to store those bits for four hours.[21] Engineer Geoff Tootill joined the team on loan from TRE in September 1947, and remained on secondment until April 1949.[22]
